{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476971","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476971"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:54:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:54:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14060"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14060","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14060"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.01,0.31,0.35,0.23]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6714"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55629"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6714","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6714"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14060"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41171"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"157"},{"type":"tags","id":"659"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1106"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13963"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17179"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44194"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55629","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55629"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA two-year-old girl presents to the Emergency Department with a 40-minute seizure associated with fever. Her parent reports that the seizure began with twitching of the right arm before becoming generalised. She has had a runny nose and cough for the past two days with temperatures up to 38.5\u00b0C. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears drowsy but responsive. Her current temperature is 38.0\u00b0C with a pulse rate of 130/min, blood pressure 90/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 28/min, and SpO2 98% on room air. Otoscopy reveals bilateral erythematous, bulging tympanic membranes. Her physical examination is otherwise unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following factors most predisposes this child to recurrent febrile seizures?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Duration of illness","Female sex","Age less than three years","Focal seizure","Temperature above 39.0\u00b0C"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child has experienced a complex febrile seizure, characterized by its focal onset and prolonged duration (\u003E15 minutes). Complex febrile seizures are associated with a higher risk of recurrence compared to simple febrile seizures, which are generalised and brief (\u0026lt;15 minutes).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Efocal seizure\u003C/strong\u003E is the factor that most predisposes this child to recurrent febrile seizures. The focality of the seizure, as evidenced by the initial twitching of the right arm, classifies this as a complex febrile seizure. Complex febrile seizures have a higher recurrence risk compared to simple febrile seizures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Eage less than three years\u003C/strong\u003E is a risk factor for febrile seizures in general, it\u0027s not as strong a predictor for recurrence as the complex nature of the seizure, particularly its focal onset.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eduration of illness\u003C/strong\u003E prior to the seizure is not typically considered a major risk factor for recurrent febrile seizures. While prolonged illness may increase the likelihood of a febrile seizure occurring, it does not significantly impact the risk of recurrence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Etemperature above 39.0\u00b0C\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with a higher risk of febrile seizures occurring. However, the height of the fever is not as significant a risk factor for recurrence as the focality and duration of the seizure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFemale sex\u003C/strong\u003E is not a significant risk factor for recurrent febrile seizures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther important risk factors for recurrent febrile seizures include a family history of febrile seizures and a short duration between fever onset and the initial seizure. However, among the options provided, the focal nature of the seizure, which makes this a complex febrile seizure, is the most significant predictor of recurrence.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Complex febrile seizures, including those with focal features, are associated with an increased risk of recurrence compared to simple febrile seizures.","The focality and duration of the seizure are more significant risk factors for recurrence than the height of the fever."],"references":["Febrile seizure. In: Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Melbourne clinical practice guidelines [online]. Accessed 2024 Aug 7. Available at: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Febrile_seizure/","Saguil A, Servey J. Predicting the Likelihood of a Recurrent Febrile Seizure. Am Fam Physician. 2020 Apr 15;101(8):497-498. Available at: https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2020/0415/p497.html"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41171"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14060"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41171","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41171"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-17T10:12:55+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-17T10:14:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6714"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55629"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"ty